title: Want To Buy:  Want to Buy Husqvarna 1900 action or rifle (or 8000 or 9000) - long action
location: From Anywhere or Flathead Valley, Kalispell, Montana
postcontent: Want to Buy Husqvarna "1900" action or rifle (or model 8000 or 9000) - long action.  No stock or barrel needed but ok if they are attached.  Going to build a 6.5x55.Will pay for action & shipping to my FFL.Here are some of the notes I compiled from various sources, of the confusing background of the HVAs and related rifles, as near as I can tell is accurate, if this helps you determine whether what you have will work for me and my MPI UL stock which I have and will use for this build:The "1900" designation is technically not the model number; but rather the general name of the action design.  However, they may be labeled simply Husqvarna (or HVA) 1900 as if that's the model number.It's a push feed, not a mauser-style controlled feed that HVA is famous for, so it's NOT the same as the Husqvarna 1600, 1640, or any of the many other Husqvarna rifles made based on the small ring mauser design.  It's a later development than those older actions - the 1900 was designed in the mid-'60s.The 1900 action was made by Husqvarna themselves from 1967 or 1968 until 1972 and imported by various companies, and was usually (confusingly) known as the "Model 1970", near as I can tell, at least for part of that time.  In addition, the model 8000 and model 9000 apparently (?) used this action, so "1900", "8000", and "9000" are the three key phrases  (along with HVA or Husqvarna).  I have also found a rifle for sale on gunbroker which is definitely a 1900 action, which purports to be a "Husqvarna Model A", but it could be erroneous auction info.When Husqvarna quit making guns in 1972, they sold the tooling and IP for the 1900 to the state run arms maker Carl Gustav (semi-private entity), and then Carl Gustav (or "CG") continued to make rifles with this action from '72 through '79, variously labeling them "FFV Carl Gustav", "FFV - Husqvarna", "HVA Carl Gustav", and "Carl Gustav (Husqvarna)".  And to add further to the confusion, CG apparently used American importers called "TradeWinds" and "Viking", so they might be labeled any of that (although the pictures I've seen of the Tradewinds catalog ads do not look the same as the 1900 actions ... maybe they are all 1600s, 1640s, or similar?).  I don't know what "FFV" stands for.In addition, for a few years, either Husqvarna or CG made rifles for Smith and Wesson, which were branded variously as S&W models:  A, B, C, D, and E.  I am very unclear as to whether any of these models are the 1900 action, and it appears that probably none of them are; however, I have seen indications that possibly the A, D, and/or E models may be the 1900 action (?).  But if you find one  labeled "S&W 1900", that would definitely be the right one.  If it's labeled one of the letter models, it may or may not be a 1900.Also, after CG quit making them, a Swedish firm started making rifles with the 1900 action in Italy, for sale inside Sweden, called the "Antonio Zoli" rifles - so it's unlikely any or many of these will be present in the USA, but if you do have a Zoli 1900, that works too.  I'm unsure, but it's possible that Zoli is still making these to this day.Very importantly, the rear bolt shroud is smooth, wide, and sleek (more futuristic looking), kind of like a Browning A-Bolt II or Weatherby Mark V, and the action has a simple forward- and backward-sliding corrugated safety, so that shroud and the safety do not look like the standard looking mauser action with the round bolt rear.Near as I can tell, on the pre-8000 / 9000 ones, they only came in ONE action length (long), so that even if you have a 1900 or "model 70" in .243, .308 etc., that will still work, as these evidently are just rifles with long actions that run short action rounds.  However, it appears as though the 8000 and 9000 ones have magnum length actions, in addition to long (and possibly short, too) - so if it's an 8000 or 9000, it probably needs to be originally a .270, .25-06, .30-06, 6.5x55, etc. (or if it's a short action round, I would just need to investigate it, so let me know short or long, but not magnum on an 8000 or 9000).If anyone happens to be able to ascertain that any of the other HVA models (Such as the S&W letter models) have the same footprint for the stock as a 1900, even if a different looking bolt shroud, please let me know.Thank you.  Text or call REDACTED.

title: For Sale:  Bronze Signal Cannon ca 1675
postcontent: This is a genuinely antique small signal cannon from Eastern Europe, likely Russia. It was made prior to 1700, and regardless of size, cannon of this age can readily be discerned by the nature of their construction. ALL bronze cannon of that age contain small short iron rods embedded in the body, which were used to keep the material in the bore centered during the casting process. These rods are called cruzettas, and in the case of a small piece such as this, are about the thickness of the lead in a mechanical pencil. They are buried within the wall of the cannon and can be located with a magnet. This is the true test of genuine age in bronze cannon. There are three such pieces in this cannon. Signal cannon were not irrelevant items on sailing ships of the period. On a ship at sail it would be nearly impossible to hear alerts or warnings that were shouted. So small cannon were fired, which were loud and caused a cloud of smoke that could be seen to let sailors know of watch changes and so forth. This piece is bronze, 5.5" long, just under 2" across the trunions, and has a bore approx 5/8". Small, but weighs about 2 pounds. This is not an item for casual collection, but is a meaningful piece of cannon history. Please email any questions.Someone asked for "provenance" for this piece. With the exception of terribly expensive cannons that were salvaged by reputable parties, or have been in known collections for years, there is no provenance except for the construction technique mentioned above. If one cannot make a reasonable and reliable determination on their own by personal inspection of what a piece is - and this applies to nearly all manner of things- then perhaps one shouldn't acquire the item.  An item speaks for itself to the knowledgeable.
